@tutialocaa I think you should read my response to the previous comment. It’s not the fault of these workers for earning minimum wage, and it’s definitely not the fault of other working-class people for not tipping. The problem is that tipping should never be mandatory — even if you’re getting the best service possible.

And the question remains: if tips are supposed to be tied to service quality, then why aren’t they “mandatory” when you get great service at McDonald’s or Foot Locker? The system is broken. Tips shouldn’t be obligatory. These workers should be paid a fair wage, and they need to stop acting entitled to tips just because their stingy bosses don’t want to pay them properly.

All of these things can be true at the same time — no opinions, just facts.

@ryan.the.bartender No one is talking about skill set, bro. This is exactly why people think bartenders come off as entitled. It’s about the quality of the service that’s presented and delivered to you. If you meet that, people will gladly tip you.

Once again, you’re telling me a Foot Locker employee shouldn’t be tipped even if they have deep knowledge about what they’re selling, make personalized recommendations, etc.? You do realize that skills are also tied to the knowledge someone can share with you, right? So why wouldn’t they deserve a tip in that case?

And if you think those workers are somehow beneath you or your so-called “skill set,” maybe you should consider a different career — since a lot of them actually make more money than you.

